[[Image:LiJinhui.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Li Jinhui]], the father of Chinese popular music]]

'''C-pop''' (Chinese: <U+4E2D><U+6587><U+6D41><U+884C><U+97F3><U+6A02> Pinyin: zhong wen liu xing yin yue Jyutping: zung man lau hang jam ngok) is an abbreviation for ''"[[China|Chinese]] [[popular music]]"''.   The majority of today's c-pop artists originate from [[Hong Kong]], [[Taiwan]], [[mainland China]] with a minority from countries such as [[Singapore]] and [[Malaysia]].  


==Terminology==
The name "Chinese Popular Music" comes from a music origin that began in [[China]] as a [[shidaiqu]] base.  There are 2 subgenre within c-pop.  [[Taiwanese pop]] may feature a similar music style, but is counted as a separate genre due to a different music root.  The term [[Tai-pop]] is used as a slang within C-pop, not an actual abbreviation.

